{"title_page": "Bosnia and Herzegovina Chess Championship", "text_new": "The '''Bosnia and Herzegovina Chess Championship''' is the national [[chess]] championship of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. It was first organised in 2005 by the BIH Chess Union; more than ten years after its independence from [[Yugoslavia]]. In the first edition there were six players from Bosnia and Herzegovina and six players from [[Serbia and Montenegro]]. The first edition was marked by the absence of leading players such as [[Borki Predojevi\u0107]], [[Bojan Kurajica]] and Emir Dizdarevi\u0107. The second edition was played with 10 players from Bosnia and Herzegovina and two players from Serbia and Montenegro. The field in the third edition consisted entirely of Bosnia and Herzegovina chess players. With Borki Predojevi\u0107 and [[Predrag Nikoli\u0107]] participating, it was the strongest edition so far.\n\n==Winners==\n:{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! # !! Year !! City !! Champion \n|-\n| 1 || 2005 || [[Br\u010dko (city)|Br\u010dko]] || {{sortname|Milan|Vukic}}\n|-\n| 2 || 2006 || [[Vitez]] || {{sortname|\u017deljko|Bogut}}\n|-\n| 3 || 2007 || [[Sarajevo]] || {{sortname|Predrag|Nikoli\u0107}}\n|-\n| 4 || 2010 || [[\u0160iroki Brijeg]] || {{sortname|\u017deljko|Bogut}}\n|-\n| 5 || 2011 || [[Cazin]] || {{sortname|Emir|Dizdarevi\u0107}}\n|-\n| 6 || 2012 || [[Neum]] || {{sortname|Emir|Dizdarevi\u0107}}\n|-\n| 7 || 2013 || [[Cazin]] || {{sortname|Denis|Kadri\u0107}}\n|-\n| 8 || 2014 || [[Zenica]] || {{sortname|Dalibor|Stojanovi\u0107|Dalibor Stojanovi\u0107 (chess player)}}\n|-\n| 9 || 2016 || [[Lukavac]] || {{sortname|Goran|Trkulja}}\n|}\n\n==Women==\n\n:{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Year !! City !! Champion \n|-\n| 2008 ||[[Ilid\u017ea]]||[[Elena Bori\u0107]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Yugoslav Chess Championship]]\n\n==External links==\n* Reports on the 2005 edition: [http://www.chesscenter.com/twic/twic582.html#8 TWIC], [http://chesslodge.blogspot.com/2005/12/1st-bosnia-herzegovina-chess.html chesslodge]\n* Reports on the 2006 edition: [http://www.bihchess.com/vitez/vitez06.htm Bichess.com]{{dead link|date=January 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n* Reports on the 2007 edition: [https://web.archive.org/web/20110930230237/http://www.chess.co.uk/twic/twic686.html#8 TWIC], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080509191822/http://www.bihchess.com/sarajevo07/index.htm Bichess.com]\n\n{{Chess national championships}}\n\n[[Category:Chess national championships]]\n[[Category:Women's chess national championships]]\n[[Category:Chess in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Championship]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Chess]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Bosnia and Herzegovina Chess Championship''' is the national [[chess]] championship of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. It was first organised in 2005 by the BIH Chess Union; more than ten years after its independence from [[Yugoslavia]]. In the first edition there were six players from Bosnia and Herzegovina and six players from [[Serbia and Montenegro]]. The first edition was marked by the absence of leading players such as [[Borki Predojevi\u0107]], [[Bojan Kurajica]] and Emir Dizdarevi\u0107. The second edition was played with 10 players from Bosnia and Herzegovina and two players from Serbia and Montenegro. The field in the third edition consisted entirely of Bosnia and Herzegovina chess players. With Borki Predojevi\u0107 and [[Predrag Nikoli\u0107]] participating, it was the strongest edition so far.\n\n==Winners==\n:{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! # !! Year !! City !! Champion \n|-\n| 1 || 2005 || [[Br\u010dko (city)|Br\u010dko]] || {{sortname|Milan|Vukic}}\n|-\n| 2 || 2006 || [[Vitez]] || {{sortname|\u017deljko|Bogut}}\n|-\n| 3 || 2007 || [[Sarajevo]] || {{sortname|Predrag|Nikoli\u0107}}\n|-\n| 4 || 2010 || [[\u0160iroki Brijeg]] || {{sortname|\u017deljko|Bogut}}\n|-\n| 5 || 2011 || [[Cazin]] || {{sortname|Emir|Dizdarevi\u0107}}\n|-\n| 6 || 2012 || [[Neum]] || {{sortname|Emir|Dizdarevi\u0107}