{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Jackson", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Jackson\n| latin             = Dioecesis Jacksoniensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Catholic cathedral of Jackson, Mississippi.jpg\n| image_size        = 200px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral of St. Peter\n| coat              = JacksonDiocese.jpg\n| coat_size         = 150px\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = United States\n| territory         = Northern and central [[Mississippi]] (65 counties)\n| province          = [[Archdiocese of Mobile|Mobile]]\n| metropolitan      = [[Thomas John Rodi]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 37,643<!-- Area in square miles, automatically converted -->\n| population        = 2,219,000\n| population_as_of  = 2013\n| catholics         = 52,900<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 2.4\n| parishes          = 74<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = July 28, 1837  ({{age|1837|07|28}} years ago)\n| cathedral         = [[Cathedral of St. Peter the Apostle (Jackson, Mississippi)|Cathedral of St. Peter the Apostle]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[St. Peter the Apostle]]\n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop            = [[Joseph R. Kopacz]]\n| metro_archbishop  = \n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Joseph Nunzio Latino]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Jackson.jpg\n| map_size          = 150px\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.jacksondiocese.org/ jacksondiocese.org]<!-- [http://example.com example.com] --> \n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe '''[[Roman Catholic]] Diocese of Jackson''' is a [[diocese]] in the [[ecclesiastical province]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Mobile|Mobile]], in the [[Southern United States|southern]] [[United States of America]]. Its ecclesiastical jurisdiction includes the northern and central parts of the state of [[Mississippi]], an area of {{convert|97,458|km2|sqmi|sp=us}}. It is the largest diocese, by area, in the United States east of the [[Mississippi River]]. It was formerly known as the ''Diocese of Natchez'' (1837\u20131956) and the ''Diocese of Natchez-Jackson'' (1956\u201377). [[Jackson, Mississippi]] is the [[episcopal see]].\n\n==History==\nThe region which is now the Diocese of Jackson made its first contacts with the Catholic Church through French [[Jesuit]] and [[Order of Friars Minor Capuchin|Capuchin]] missionaries during the expeditions of [[Ren\u00e9-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle|La Salle]], [[Jacques Marquette|Marquette]], and [[Pierre Le Moyne d'Iberville|d'Iberville]] in the 17th and 18th centuries. In 1787, three [[Spain|Spanish]] priests, Fathers McKenna, White, and Savage, arrived at [[Natchez, Mississippi|Natchez]] from [[Salamanca]] and erected three missions in the vicinity. These missions, however, virtually disappeared after the Spanish turned over the area to the United States. Much valuable property was lost to the Church, and the efforts made to recover it were in vain.<ref name=Charles>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/10709b.htm Charles, Brother. \"Natchez.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 10. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 26 February 2020{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nThe diocese was originally erected as the '''Vicariate Apostolic of Mississippi''', an administrative region of the church separate from the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of New Orleans|Diocese of Louisiana and the Two Floridas (Saint Louis of New Orleans)]] to which it had previously belonged, and which itself would later become the Diocese of New Orleans on 18 July 1826. At the head of the Vicariate was [[Louis-Guillaume-Valentin Dubourg]], P.S.S., who served less than a year before being appointed [[bishop of Montauban]], [[France]] (he would eventually become the [[archbishop of Besan\u00e7on]]).\n\nThe Vicariate was elevated to the '''[[Natchesium|Diocese of Natchez]]''' on 28 July 1837. Although the Diocese of Natchez encompassed the entire state of Mississippi, nearly three years passed before [[John Mary Joseph Chanche]], S.S. (1795\u20131852), president of [[St. Mary's Seminary and University|St. Mary's College]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], was appointed as its first bishop on 15 December 1840.  Bishop Chanche, like his predecessor, was of French lineage, having been born to parents who had fled to Baltimore from the French colony of [[Saint-Domingue]] (present-day [[Haiti]]), presumably during the Haitian revolution. At his arrival in Mississippi, he found one priest in the diocese, a Father Brogard, who was there only temporarily. Chanche set to work building a diocesan infrastructure. \n\nIn 1842 Bishop Chanche laid the cornerstone of the [[St. Mary Basilica, Natchez|Cathedral of Our Lady of Sorrows]], designed by [[Robert Cary Long Jr.]] After the diocesan see was translated to Jackson, this became St. Mary's Basilica. In 1847 the [[Daughters of Charity of Saint Vincent de Paul|Sisters of Charity]] of Emmitsburg came to Natchez and established Saint Mary's Orphanage.<ref> [https://books.google.com/books?id=yt0Xrt7vcVYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=St.+Mary+Basilica,+Natchez&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwitg_y78dbnAhUsVd8KHfAOCFM4ChDoATAIegQIBxAC#v=onepage&q=St.%20Mary%20Basilica%2C%20Natchez&f=false Namorato, Michael V., ''The Catholic Church in Mississippi, 1911-1984: A History'', Greenwood Publishing Group, 1998, p. 7]{{ISBN|9780313307195}}</ref> Chanche attended the [[Plenary Councils of Baltimore|First Plenary Council]] of 1852, held in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]. While returning to Natchez, he died at [[Frederick, Maryland]], presumably of cholera.<ref name=archb>[https://www.archbalt.org/body-of-first-bishop-of-mississippi-exhumed-in-baltimore/ \"Body of first bishop of Mississippi exhumed in Baltimore\", Archdiocese of Baltimore]</ref> He had built 11 churches, with a team of 11 priests and 13 attendant missions.\n\nA curious series of events regarding the separation of church and state involved the [[Diocese of Natchez]] in 1864, during the [[American Civil War]]. That year, Bishop [[William Henry Elder]] refused to bend to orders from the Federal troops administering Natchez to compel his parishioners to pray for the [[President of the United States]]. For this act, Elder was tried, convicted, and then jailed briefly in [[Vidalia, Louisiana]], just across the [[Mississippi River]] from Natchez. Elder wrote to President Lincoln explaining that his refusal was not political, but based on the authority of the church to regulate church services. After officials in Washington intervened, Elder was ordered released on 12 August 1864.<ref name=glimpses>''Character Glimpses of Most Reverend William Henry Elder, D.D.,'' published by Frederick Pustet & Company, New York and Cincinnati, 1911</ref> As of 2006, Elder remains the second-longest-serving bishop in the diocese's history.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nBy the mid-20th century, the capitol of the state of Mississippi, [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]], had grown to perhaps be a more appropriate center for the administration of the diocese. To reflect this fact, on 18 December 1956 the name was changed to '''Diocese of Natchez-Jackson'''. Finally, on 1 March 1977, the diocese was divided, with the southern counties of Mississippi being reorganized as the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Biloxi|Diocese of Biloxi]]. Concurrently, the Diocese of Natchez-Jackson became simply the Diocese of Jackson.  Since the relocation of the diocese to Jackson, the Diocese of Natchez has been maintained as a [[titular see]].\n\n===Sex Abuse===\nIn 2006, the Diocese of Jackson, Mississippi, settled a handful of lawsuits with 19 victims with a $5 million settlement which included an average payout of more than $250,000 for each survivor. In August 2019, it was revealed that a 35 year-old man named La Jarvis D. Love was sexually abused at a Franciscan Friar grade school in Greenwood, Mississippi when he was a boy and that Order attempted to keep him silent in later years by offering him $15,000.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/nbcblk/catholic-church-settles-sex-abuse-case-southern-black-man-n1046816 \"Catholic church settles sex abuse case with Southern black man\"]</ref> Love and Wisconsin-based Franciscan Friar leader James Gannon secretly signed a non-disclosure agreement in January 2019 which insured that the order would give Love a financial settlement. This came in spite of the fact that the Catholic Church agreed to ban non-disclosure agreements. By August 30, the accused friar's name was revealed to be Paul West and Love's three cousins Joshua Love, La Jarvis Love and Raphael Love also accused him of sexually abusing them in the mid 1990s.<ref name=loveaccusations>[https://msbusiness.com/2019/08/survivors-demand-us-investigation-of-mississippi-abuse-deals/ \"Survivors demand US investigation of Mississippi abuse deals\"]</ref> \n\n==Demographics==\nThe first seat of the diocese was [[St. Mary Basilica, Natchez|Saint Mary Basilica]] (then Cathedral) in Natchez, whose cornerstone was laid by Bishop Chanche in 1842. The current seat is the [[Cathedral of St. Peter the Apostle in Jackson]]. Since 1998, however, the church has maintained a [[minor basilica]] at the former cathedral in Natchez; it is now formally known as St. Mary Basilica.\n\nThe Diocese of Jackson encompasses an area of the United States that has historically been (and still is) overwhelmingly Protestant. Only about 2.6% of the residents in the diocese are considered Catholic (about 52,000 Catholics out of a total population of nearly 2 million). The diocese contains 74 [[parish]]es and has 79 priests.\n\n==Bishops==\n===Bishops of Natchez===\n# [[John J. Chanche]], P.S.S. (1840\u20131852)\n# [[James Oliver Van de Velde]], S.J. (1853\u20131855)\n# [[William Henry Elder]] (1857\u20131880), appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cincinnati|Archbishop of Cincinnati]]\n# [[Francis Janssens]] (1881\u20131888), appointed [[Archbishop of New Orleans]]\n# [[Thomas Heslin]] (1889\u20131911)\n# [[John Edward Gunn]], S.M. (1911\u20131924)\n\n===Bishop of Natchez-Jackson===\n# [[Richard Oliver Gerow]] (1924\u20131967)\n\n===Bishops of Jackson===\n# [[Joseph Bernard Brunini]] (1967\u20131984)\n# [[William Russell Houck]] (1984\u20132003)\n# [[Joseph Nunzio Latino]] (2003\u20132013)\n# [[Joseph R. Kopacz]] (2014\u2013present)\n\n===Auxiliary Bishop===\n* [[William Russell Houck]] (1979\u20131984), appointed Bishop of Jackson\n\n===Other priests of this diocese who became bishops===\n* [[Bernard Francis Law]], appointed Bishop of Springfield-Cape Girardeau in 1973; future Cardinal\n* [[Ronald Paul Herzog]] (priest here, 1968-1977), appointed Bishop of Alexandria in 2004\n\n==Schools==\n\n===Middle Schools and High Schools===\n*[[Cathedral High School (Natchez, Mississippi)|Cathedral Middle/High School]] ([[Natchez, Mississippi|Natchez]])\n*[[St. Aloysius High School (Vicksburg, Mississippi)|St. Aloysius Middle/High School]] ([[Vicksburg, Mississippi|Vicksburg]])\n*[[St. Joseph Catholic High School (Greenville, Mississippi)|St. Joseph Catholic High School]] ([[Greenville, Mississippi|Greenville]])\n*[[St. Joseph Catholic High School (Madison, Mississippi)|St. Joseph Catholic High School]] ([[Madison, Mississippi|Madison]])\n\n===Elementary Schools===\n*Annunciation Catholic Elementary School ([[Columbus, Mississippi|Columbus]])\n*Cathedral Elementary School (Natchez)\n*Holy Child Jesus Elementary School ([[Canton, Mississippi|Canton]])\n*Holy Family Elementary School ([[Holly Springs, Mississippi|Holly Springs]])\n*Our Lady of Lourdes Elementary School (Greenville)\n*Sacred Heart Elementary School ([[Southaven, Mississippi|Southaven]])\n*St. Alphonsus Elementary School ([[McComb, Mississippi|McComb]])\n*St. Anthony Elementary School ([[Madison, Mississippi|Madison]])\n*St. Elizabeth Elementary School ([[Clarksdale, Mississippi|Clarksdale]])\n*St. Francis of Assisi Elementary School ([[Greenwood, Mississippi|Greenwood]])\n*St. Francis Elementary School (Vicksburg)\n*St. Patrick Elementary School ([[Meridian, Mississippi|Meridian]])\n*St. Therese Elementary School (Jackson)\n*St. Richard Catholic School (Jackson)\n*Sister Thea Bowman Catholic School (Jackson)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n* [[Catholic Church hierarchy]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n* [[Natchesium]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{catholic|title=Natchez}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jacksondiocese.org/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Jackson Official Site]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Jackson}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Mobile}}\n{{Jackson, Mississippi}}\n{{coord|32|17|56|N|90|11|05|W|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roman Catholic Diocese Of Jackson}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Mobile]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Culture of Jackson, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:1837 establishments in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Dioces